Setups? Platforms? There were no setups. There were no platforms. One screen. I used the phone to call orders long-distance direct to trading floors around the world. Ran a phone bill of $800 per month.
Technology changed rapidly in early 1980s. This sat dish (circa 1983 roof left) connected with Commodity Quote Graphics  still a leader in trading technology and a firm I use for order placement.
Frankly I hate the word Hodlers. Use English people over 40 can understand. Don't understand how a person who sat through a 70% price drop can take that as a sign of honor.
Eventually went to mini dishes. This one (roof on left) connected with Commodity Quote Graphics (CQG) a firm I still use for order placement.
There were literally dozens of satellites in the sky. I need to go outside and physically rotate the dish. Drilled holes in a metal sliding pole to market different satellites.
We would just tape a new graph -- sometimes sideways, sometimes diagonally.

In the late 70's and early 80's we Dinosaurs finally could get price data via satellite dishes. Until then ATT long-time was the only way. With satellite dishes I could get almost instantaneous price reporting.
Computers spitting out charts did not exist in 1975. This is a Copper P&F chart I kept by hand. We used graph paper to hand create price charts. $HG_F
Dinosaur This is what the Chicago Board of Trade floor looked like when I entered the business. Note the prices were kept on clicker-boards and by hand on black-boards.
